WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:900000,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:00:36.453 --> 00:00:38.038 position:50% align:center
[SUGIMOTO]
Toh! Toh! Toh!

00:00:39.122 --> 00:00:40.665 position:50% align:center
Keep it up!

00:00:40.749 --> 00:00:43.668 position:50% align:center
I can't believe how quickly
the weather turned!

00:00:43.752 --> 00:00:45.545 position:50% align:center
We need to get somewhere safe!

00:00:50.383 --> 00:00:52.802 position:50% align:center
[TANIGAKI groans]
I can't even see anymore!

00:00:54.763 --> 00:00:56.639 position:50% align:center
Ryu! What're you doing, boy?

00:00:56.723 --> 00:00:58.433 position:50% align:center
You stay in formation!

00:00:58.516 --> 00:01:01.144 position:50% align:center
Don't you think he mighta
spotted something?

00:01:01.227 --> 00:01:03.938 position:50% align:center
[SUGIMOTO] Nah, Ryu was
never cut out to pull a sled!

00:01:04.022 --> 00:01:05.565 position:50% align:center
He's a hunting dog!

00:01:07.859 --> 00:01:09.903 position:50% align:center
[SUGIMOTO]
Ryu! Where are you going?

00:01:09.986 --> 00:01:11.821 position:50% align:center
Ya gotta go straight!

00:01:14.783 --> 00:01:18.078 position:50% align:center
Henke says he can see something!
Just up ahead!

00:01:18.161 --> 00:01:19.245 position:50% align:center
[HAJIME]
Stop the sled!

00:01:19.329 --> 00:01:21.581 position:50% align:center
I can't see the others
behind us anymore!

00:01:25.960 --> 00:01:27.504 position:50% align:center
Sugimoto!

00:01:30.090 --> 00:01:31.591 position:50% align:center
[TANIGAKI]
Was that a gunshot?

00:01:31.675 --> 00:01:33.259 position:50% align:center
Did we get separated?

00:01:34.803 --> 00:01:37.222 position:50% align:center
[SUGIMOTO] Which direction
did it come from?

00:01:37.305 --> 00:01:39.057 position:50% align:center
I think it was that way!

00:01:39.140 --> 00:01:40.600 position:50% align:center
[TANIGAKI growls]

00:01:46.773 --> 00:01:49.401 position:50% align:center
Hey! Did anybody hear anything?

00:01:49.484 --> 00:01:51.027 position:50% align:center
[KOITO]
What'd you say?

00:01:54.864 --> 00:01:56.074 position:50% align:center
[SUGIMOTO]
It's no good!

00:01:56.157 --> 00:01:57.575 position:50% align:center
We need to find shelter!

00:01:57.659 --> 00:02:00.203 position:50% align:center
At the very least,
we gotta get outta this wind!

00:02:00.286 --> 00:02:02.205 position:50% align:center
We have to find something.

00:02:09.004 --> 00:02:10.088 position:50% align:center
[SUGIMOTO]
What?

00:02:10.171 --> 00:02:13.508 position:50% align:center
We came all
the way to the coast?

00:02:13.591 --> 00:02:16.845 position:50% align:center
Not good.
We need to move quickly.

00:02:16.928 --> 00:02:18.346 position:50% align:center
Or we're dead!

00:03:54.359 --> 00:03:58.780 position:50% align:center
[SUGIMOTO grunting]

00:03:58.863 --> 00:03:59.948 position:50% align:center
Damn it!

00:04:00.031 --> 00:04:04.369 position:50% align:center
[growls] No use!
The ground's frozen solid!

00:04:04.452 --> 00:04:06.788 position:50% align:center
[TANIGAKI grunts]
We need to try something else.

00:04:06.871 --> 00:04:08.581 position:50% align:center
Destroy the sled.

00:04:11.793 --> 00:04:13.086 position:50% align:center
[KOITO]
Tsukishima!

00:04:13.169 --> 00:04:15.380 position:50% align:center
We're in real danger here!

00:04:18.591 --> 00:04:19.884 position:50% align:center
Let's go!

00:04:19.968 --> 00:04:22.470 position:50% align:center
We'll head towards whatever
the old man saw before!

00:04:28.643 --> 00:04:30.145 position:50% align:center
All right!

00:04:30.228 --> 00:04:32.313 position:50% align:center
--[TANIGAKI grunts]
--A-Ah!

00:04:32.397 --> 00:04:34.524 position:50% align:center
What are you doing?!

00:04:34.607 --> 00:04:36.818 position:50% align:center
A sled's worth of firewood
won't last long enough

00:04:36.901 --> 00:04:38.737 position:50% align:center
to do us any good.

00:04:38.820 --> 00:04:43.074 position:50% align:center
If we bury it, it'll burn
slowly in the earth.

00:04:43.158 --> 00:04:46.995 position:50% align:center
So, if we lie down on it, we can
stay warm a little longer.

00:04:47.078 --> 00:04:50.915 position:50% align:center
[SUGIMOTO] Hmph. That's right, I
almost forgot, you're a Matagi.

00:04:50.999 --> 00:04:52.625 position:50% align:center
[TANIGAKI]
But the hole's not deep enough.

00:04:52.709 --> 00:04:55.128 position:50% align:center
It'll just keep the wind off.

00:04:55.211 --> 00:04:57.088 position:50% align:center
You guys! Come here!

00:05:01.009 --> 00:05:03.928 position:50% align:center
A dog blanket.
It does the trick.

00:05:06.181 --> 00:05:09.017 position:50% align:center
But are you sure
the dogs will be okay?

00:05:09.100 --> 00:05:10.268 position:50% align:center
[TANIGAKI]
They're fine.

00:05:10.352 --> 00:05:13.897 position:50% align:center
Thankfully, they handle
the cold extremely well.

00:05:13.980 --> 00:05:16.232 position:50% align:center
Not sure how long
we'll last, though.

00:05:17.776 --> 00:05:19.736 position:50% align:center
[TANIGAKI]
The sun will set soon.

00:05:22.489 --> 00:05:24.657 position:50% align:center
[KOITO]
Look, there're cows here!

00:05:24.741 --> 00:05:26.785 position:50% align:center
Whose are they?

00:05:26.868 --> 00:05:31.206 position:50% align:center
We can worry about that later.
For now, let's start a fire.

00:05:31.289 --> 00:05:33.249 position:50% align:center
Well, what about the others?

00:05:33.333 --> 00:05:38.129 position:50% align:center
With Tanigaki... they should
be okay, for a while.

00:05:42.550 --> 00:05:46.971 position:50% align:center
Here. There's not much, but
eating makes a big difference

00:05:47.055 --> 00:05:49.974 position:50% align:center
when trying to maintain
your temperature.

00:05:50.058 --> 00:05:52.727 position:50% align:center
Open up. There ya go

00:05:55.522 --> 00:05:56.940 position:50% align:center
Wait, what is this?

00:05:57.023 --> 00:05:59.734 position:50% align:center
I feel like I've
definitely had it before.

00:05:59.818 --> 00:06:01.569 position:50% align:center
Not possible.

00:06:01.653 --> 00:06:03.988 position:50% align:center
This is a secret
recipe for mochi.

00:06:04.072 --> 00:06:07.992 position:50% align:center
It comes from where I grew up,
but I've changed it a little.

00:06:08.076 --> 00:06:13.289 position:50% align:center
Oh, yeah, you sure?
That's really strange.

00:06:13.373 --> 00:06:16.292 position:50% align:center
Because I'm pretty sure
that I remember eating this.

00:06:18.086 --> 00:06:21.631 position:50% align:center
[bang echoing]

00:06:21.715 --> 00:06:23.133 position:50% align:center
Well, what's your guess?

00:06:23.216 --> 00:06:25.343 position:50% align:center
Gunshot or thunder?

00:06:25.427 --> 00:06:28.346 position:50% align:center
In the middle of a blizzard, you
can be shouting at each other

00:06:28.430 --> 00:06:30.849 position:50% align:center
from a few feet away
and still get lost.

00:06:30.932 --> 00:06:33.184 position:50% align:center
It's a waking nightmare.

00:06:33.268 --> 00:06:36.354 position:50% align:center
You can't trust your ears
or your sense of direction.

00:06:41.443 --> 00:06:45.613 position:50% align:center
[MAN 31A speaks Russian]

00:06:45.697 --> 00:06:47.866 position:50% align:center
The man who lives here?

00:06:47.949 --> 00:06:50.952 position:50% align:center
[HAJIME speaks Russian]

00:06:51.036 --> 00:06:54.122 position:50% align:center
[MAN 31A
growls, speaks in Russian]

00:06:56.541 --> 00:06:58.626 position:50% align:center
[MAN 31A speaks Russian]

00:07:08.219 --> 00:07:09.929 position:50% align:center
[MAN 31A speaks Russian]

00:07:12.307 --> 00:07:13.558 position:50% align:center
[gasps]

00:07:15.602 --> 00:07:21.858 position:50% align:center
[MAN 31A speaks Russian]

00:07:21.941 --> 00:07:24.277 position:50% align:center
--[KOITO gasps]
--What is this?

00:07:26.571 --> 00:07:29.324 position:50% align:center
[TANIGAKI]
This reminds me of the trenches.

00:07:29.407 --> 00:07:31.534 position:50% align:center
Laying in a cold hole.

00:07:31.618 --> 00:07:32.994 position:50% align:center
Yeah.

00:07:35.455 --> 00:07:37.957 position:50% align:center
Don't go to sleep, Sugimoto.

00:07:38.041 --> 00:07:40.418 position:50% align:center
You'll die.

00:07:40.502 --> 00:07:42.087 position:50% align:center
Right...

00:07:44.130 --> 00:07:46.341 position:50% align:center
It's damn cold.

00:07:50.679 --> 00:07:52.931 position:50% align:center
It's really cold, Toraji.

00:07:53.932 --> 00:07:56.267 position:50% align:center
I wanna go home, Saichi.

00:07:56.351 --> 00:07:59.354 position:50% align:center
[sobbing]

00:08:01.690 --> 00:08:03.400 position:50% align:center
I want to go home...

00:08:07.070 --> 00:08:12.826 position:50% align:center
[SUGIMOTO panting]

00:08:12.909 --> 00:08:17.497 position:50% align:center
--[blows landing]
--[RUSSIAN SOLDIERS groaning]

00:08:17.580 --> 00:08:19.416 position:50% align:center
Heh...

00:08:20.709 --> 00:08:25.171 position:50% align:center
[panting]

00:08:30.677 --> 00:08:32.387 position:50% align:center
[ASIRPA]
Sugimoto...

00:08:32.470 --> 00:08:36.016 position:50% align:center
[SUGIMOTO gasps]
Asirpa...

00:08:37.017 --> 00:08:39.185 position:50% align:center
Sugimoto...

00:08:46.860 --> 00:08:49.362 position:50% align:center
Is that a... light?

00:08:50.655 --> 00:08:53.450 position:50% align:center
You guys... the light.
Can you see it?

00:08:53.533 --> 00:08:55.326 position:50% align:center
Is it the moon?

00:08:55.410 --> 00:09:00.290 position:50% align:center
No. It's been exactly two months
since we attacked Abashiri.

00:09:00.373 --> 00:09:03.043 position:50% align:center
The moon shouldn't be that big.

00:09:03.126 --> 00:09:06.671 position:50% align:center
[SUGIMOTO] It's flickering.
That's not moonlight.

00:09:06.755 --> 00:09:08.715 position:50% align:center
Wait, is that...?

00:09:08.798 --> 00:09:10.216 position:50% align:center
It's a lighthouse!

00:09:11.760 --> 00:09:13.428 position:50% align:center
[HAJIME]
Lieutenant.

00:09:13.511 --> 00:09:15.305 position:50% align:center
Lieutenant Koito.

00:09:15.388 --> 00:09:18.183 position:50% align:center
Please don't wander
in front of the lens.

00:09:18.266 --> 00:09:22.103 position:50% align:center
You're blocking all the light.

00:09:22.187 --> 00:09:24.272 position:50% align:center
[KOITO sighs]

00:09:24.356 --> 00:09:28.026 position:50% align:center
[GROUP panting]

00:09:29.235 --> 00:09:35.492 position:50% align:center
[panting]

00:09:37.410 --> 00:09:40.622 position:50% align:center
[KOITO] This "sushka"
goes well with tea.

00:09:40.705 --> 00:09:42.832 position:50% align:center
You know what I'd really love?

00:09:42.916 --> 00:09:45.919 position:50% align:center
To see Lieutenant Tsurumi
try this out.

00:09:48.296 --> 00:09:50.382 position:50% align:center
[MAN 31A speaks Russian]

00:09:51.633 --> 00:09:54.844 position:50% align:center
The warmest spot in this
room's above the pechka,

00:09:54.928 --> 00:09:57.639 position:50% align:center
and the Russians
sleep there, too.

00:09:57.722 --> 00:10:00.725 position:50% align:center
[KOITO chuckles]
They look like bugs.

00:10:04.020 --> 00:10:06.272 position:50% align:center
Well, you all got lucky.

00:10:07.816 --> 00:10:09.359 position:50% align:center
[HAJIME] This lighthouse
hasn't been used

00:10:09.442 --> 00:10:12.070 position:50% align:center
since the Russo-Japanese War.

00:10:12.153 --> 00:10:14.114 position:50% align:center
And if these people
hadn't been here.

00:10:14.197 --> 00:10:17.492 position:50% align:center
You would've been
frozen solid by now.

00:10:17.575 --> 00:10:19.244 position:50% align:center
[speaks Russian]

00:10:19.327 --> 00:10:21.371 position:50% align:center
[laughs]

00:10:29.838 --> 00:10:32.632 position:50% align:center
[SUGIMOTO] I'm really sorry
we burned your sled.

00:10:34.050 --> 00:10:35.719 position:50% align:center
What? You're done?

00:10:35.802 --> 00:10:39.014 position:50% align:center
Wow, you really just made this
with whatever was lying around?

00:10:39.097 --> 00:10:40.974 position:50% align:center
Amazing, Henke!

00:10:41.057 --> 00:10:44.185 position:50% align:center
[HAJIME] Okay, looks like
we're all set to go!

00:10:44.269 --> 00:10:48.857 position:50% align:center
Looking back, I think the reason
Ryu broke off from the line...

00:10:48.940 --> 00:10:52.235 position:50% align:center
...was because he was trying
to stay with the other sled.

00:10:53.278 --> 00:10:55.405 position:50% align:center
Sorry for doubting you.

00:10:55.488 --> 00:10:58.324 position:50% align:center
Who's a good dog? You are!

00:10:58.408 --> 00:11:01.369 position:50% align:center
You could be
a great sled dog, too!

00:11:01.453 --> 00:11:02.787 position:50% align:center
[barks]

00:11:02.871 --> 00:11:06.708 position:50% align:center
Tsukishima! This hammer
just froze to my hand!

00:11:06.791 --> 00:11:08.877 position:50% align:center
That's what happens if you
touch metal bare-handed

00:11:08.960 --> 00:11:10.420 position:50% align:center
at this temperature.

00:11:10.503 --> 00:11:13.131 position:50% align:center
If you rip it off, you could
tear away the skin.

00:11:15.300 --> 00:11:17.802 position:50% align:center
All right. Who wants to
pee on it for him?

00:11:17.886 --> 00:11:19.846 position:50% align:center
[KOITO]
Uh...

00:11:19.929 --> 00:11:21.389 position:50% align:center
Guess I can do it.

00:11:27.979 --> 00:11:29.481 position:50% align:center
[SUGIMOTO]
Gimme your hand.

00:11:41.409 --> 00:11:42.994 position:50% align:center
This soup is bright red!

00:11:43.078 --> 00:11:44.871 position:50% align:center
What is it?

00:11:44.954 --> 00:11:47.040 position:50% align:center
[HAJIME]
Yes, this is borscht.

00:11:47.123 --> 00:11:50.210 position:50% align:center
The red comes from
a vegetable called a "beet."

00:11:50.293 --> 00:11:52.587 position:50% align:center
Hey, what's the Russian
word for "yummy"?

00:11:52.671 --> 00:11:54.714 position:50% align:center
[HAJIME]
Hmm... [speaks Russian]

00:11:54.798 --> 00:11:58.760 position:50% align:center
[ALL saying "Yummy" in Russian]

00:11:58.843 --> 00:12:02.555 position:50% align:center
[speaking Russian]

00:12:02.639 --> 00:12:04.849 position:50% align:center
It's normally just them,
so they're happy

00:12:04.933 --> 00:12:06.685 position:50% align:center
to have the company.

00:12:06.768 --> 00:12:09.229 position:50% align:center
Just you? No family?

00:12:10.438 --> 00:12:13.483 position:50% align:center
Is that your daughter
in that photo there?

00:12:13.566 --> 00:12:15.235 position:50% align:center
[BOTH sigh]

00:12:16.236 --> 00:12:18.571 position:50% align:center
What's wrong?

00:12:18.655 --> 00:12:21.533 position:50% align:center
[speaking Russian]

00:12:21.616 --> 00:12:23.952 position:50% align:center
The three of them had lived
here together in peace,

00:12:24.035 --> 00:12:26.996 position:50% align:center
watching over the lighthouse
since before the war.

00:12:27.080 --> 00:12:30.208 position:50% align:center
It was a good life.

00:12:30.291 --> 00:12:33.545 position:50% align:center
But one day, a Russian deserter
appeared and ended up

00:12:33.628 --> 00:12:36.881 position:50% align:center
lodging with them for a while.

00:12:36.965 --> 00:12:39.676 position:50% align:center
According to them,
when he finally left,

00:12:39.759 --> 00:12:43.471 position:50% align:center
he took their
only daughter with him.

00:12:43.555 --> 00:12:46.558 position:50% align:center
They searched for her,
but they didn't find her.

00:12:46.641 --> 00:12:48.643 position:50% align:center
Neither the military nor
the government did anything

00:12:48.727 --> 00:12:52.105 position:50% align:center
to help them.

00:12:52.188 --> 00:12:55.233 position:50% align:center
When the Japanese landed on
the shores of Karafuto,

00:12:55.316 --> 00:12:57.861 position:50% align:center
the Russian government gave
the couple explosives to destroy

00:12:57.944 --> 00:13:02.824 position:50% align:center
the lighthouse, to keep it from
being used by the Japanese.

00:13:02.907 --> 00:13:05.410 position:50% align:center
But they were so angry with the
Russian government that they

00:13:05.493 --> 00:13:09.122 position:50% align:center
handed it over to
the Japanese anyway.

00:13:09.205 --> 00:13:11.541 position:50% align:center
Later, another lighthouse
was built to the north,

00:13:11.624 --> 00:13:14.586 position:50% align:center
so there was
no need for this place.

00:13:14.669 --> 00:13:15.670 position:50% align:center
[WOMAN 31A sobbing]

00:13:15.754 --> 00:13:17.380 position:50% align:center
[HAJIME]
But the two of them remain here.

00:13:17.464 --> 00:13:20.091 position:50% align:center
Still hoping their daughter
might someday return.

00:13:20.175 --> 00:13:22.719 position:50% align:center
[sobbing]

00:13:22.802 --> 00:13:26.473 position:50% align:center
[wails]

00:13:30.518 --> 00:13:34.064 position:50% align:center
So, because of their daughter,
and their tragedy,

00:13:34.147 --> 00:13:38.902 position:50% align:center
the lighthouse remained.
and we're still alive.

00:13:38.985 --> 00:13:40.987 position:50% align:center
[SUGIMOTO]
Maybe we can help.

00:13:41.071 --> 00:13:42.822 position:50% align:center
Can I take this photo?

00:13:46.076 --> 00:13:48.453 position:50% align:center
What's her name?

00:13:48.536 --> 00:13:50.205 position:50% align:center
[WOMAN 31A]
Svetlana....

00:13:53.625 --> 00:13:55.877 position:50% align:center
[HAJIME speaks Russian]

00:13:55.960 --> 00:14:00.965 position:50% align:center
[WOMAN 31A speaks Russian]

00:14:03.551 --> 00:14:05.762 position:50% align:center
Great. Good job.

00:14:05.845 --> 00:14:07.263 position:50% align:center
Look, I know.

00:14:07.347 --> 00:14:10.767 position:50% align:center
But it won't take too much time
to ask around on our way.

00:14:10.850 --> 00:14:14.521 position:50% align:center
I can't leave them without
doing something in return.

00:14:14.604 --> 00:14:16.940 position:50% align:center
Ma'am, would you mind
putting this photo of mine

00:14:17.023 --> 00:14:19.067 position:50% align:center
in that empty frame?

00:14:19.150 --> 00:14:23.238 position:50% align:center
And if this Ainu girl comes by,
please give her a message.

00:14:23.321 --> 00:14:25.907 position:50% align:center
Saichi Sugimoto is alive.

00:14:27.909 --> 00:14:29.452 position:50% align:center
[SUGIMOTO]
Okay, go!

00:14:31.329 --> 00:14:34.207 position:50% align:center
Toh, toh, toh, toh, toh!

00:14:50.807 --> 00:14:52.976 position:50% align:center
[SUGIMOTO]
Asirpa, her name is Asirpa.

00:14:53.059 --> 00:14:55.395 position:50% align:center
[AINU BOYS speaking Ainu]

00:14:55.478 --> 00:14:56.771 position:50% align:center
[SUGIMOTO]
Okay, well.

00:14:56.855 --> 00:14:57.939 position:50% align:center
What about her?

00:14:58.023 --> 00:15:01.067 position:50% align:center
[AINU BOYS speaking Ainu]

00:15:01.151 --> 00:15:03.737 position:50% align:center
[NARRATOR] At this time,
Sugimoto's group was staying

00:15:03.820 --> 00:15:08.491 position:50% align:center
at a Karafuto Ainu
village near Niitoi.

00:15:08.575 --> 00:15:10.577 position:50% align:center
There were only a hundred
and forty kilometers left

00:15:10.660 --> 00:15:12.912 position:50% align:center
to reach the border.

00:15:12.996 --> 00:15:14.497 position:50% align:center
[ENONAKA]
Cikapasi.

00:15:14.581 --> 00:15:18.626 position:50% align:center
Listen, a meko oyasi
was sighted in this village!

00:15:18.710 --> 00:15:21.087 position:50% align:center
What's that? Is it scary?

00:15:21.171 --> 00:15:22.630 position:50% align:center
[ENONAKA] It's a cat monster
from the legends

00:15:22.714 --> 00:15:26.009 position:50% align:center
of Karafuto Ainu!

00:15:26.092 --> 00:15:29.387 position:50% align:center
Someone dropped all their stuff
on the beach and went to work,

00:15:29.471 --> 00:15:31.765 position:50% align:center
and a meko oyasi appeared!

00:15:31.848 --> 00:15:34.267 position:50% align:center
They fled on their ship, and
then a bunch of the things

00:15:34.351 --> 00:15:36.186 position:50% align:center
suddenly appeared on the beach!

00:15:36.269 --> 00:15:38.605 position:50% align:center
Staring at the ship,
howling and yowling!

00:15:38.688 --> 00:15:40.607 position:50% align:center
[CIKAPASI gasps]

00:15:40.690 --> 00:15:42.984 position:50% align:center
[ENONAKA] It's a big cat
the size of a dog,

00:15:43.068 --> 00:15:46.321 position:50% align:center
and it has red and white spots!

00:15:46.404 --> 00:15:48.573 position:50% align:center
A large mountain cat.

00:15:48.656 --> 00:15:52.243 position:50% align:center
Heh. Or, maybe
it's actually Ogata?

00:15:52.327 --> 00:15:54.454 position:50% align:center
[SUGIMOTO]
Wait, why Ogata?

00:15:57.248 --> 00:16:01.211 position:50% align:center
The child of a mountain cat's
a mountain cat.

00:16:01.294 --> 00:16:03.296 position:50% align:center
What's that mean?

00:16:03.380 --> 00:16:06.508 position:50% align:center
"Mountain cat" is a slang term
used for geisha.

00:16:06.591 --> 00:16:08.551 position:50% align:center
Men in the division
used to say it.

00:16:08.635 --> 00:16:10.970 position:50% align:center
It was always a dumb joke.

00:16:11.054 --> 00:16:13.390 position:50% align:center
Yeah, that really is dumb.

00:16:13.473 --> 00:16:15.600 position:50% align:center
Considering what he's like,
a lot of the men

00:16:15.684 --> 00:16:17.519 position:50% align:center
couldn't stand him.

00:16:17.602 --> 00:16:20.980 position:50% align:center
I hate him even now.

00:16:21.064 --> 00:16:23.858 position:50% align:center
There's another common meaning
for "mountain cat"--

00:16:23.942 --> 00:16:27.445 position:50% align:center
a person who cons
or deceives someone.

00:16:27.529 --> 00:16:30.115 position:50% align:center
Perfect for him, right?

00:16:30.198 --> 00:16:32.575 position:50% align:center
What do you think?
Am I wrong?

00:16:34.619 --> 00:16:37.497 position:50% align:center
[CIKAPASI] So, what happened
with the meko oyasi?

00:16:37.580 --> 00:16:39.624 position:50% align:center
When the person
came back later,

00:16:39.708 --> 00:16:41.334 position:50% align:center
there were lots of
paw prints everywhere,

00:16:41.418 --> 00:16:43.128 position:50% align:center
and all their stuff was gone.

00:16:43.211 --> 00:16:45.755 position:50% align:center
Their clothes,
their bags--all of it!

00:16:45.839 --> 00:16:48.883 position:50% align:center
[gasps]
They ate it?

00:16:48.967 --> 00:16:50.385 position:50% align:center
[ENONOKA]
Maybe.

00:16:50.468 --> 00:16:53.638 position:50% align:center
[CIKAPASI whimpers]
Tobacco cases...?

00:16:53.722 --> 00:16:56.433 position:50% align:center
No. I think those stink too bad.

00:16:56.516 --> 00:16:58.435 position:50% align:center
They wouldn't eat them.

00:16:58.518 --> 00:17:00.562 position:50% align:center
Scary.

00:17:00.645 --> 00:17:04.357 position:50% align:center
If there's any lesson to be
had in that bizarre story...

00:17:04.441 --> 00:17:08.111 position:50% align:center
...it's that thieving cat
should be killed. Dead.

00:17:22.292 --> 00:17:25.545 position:50% align:center
[ASIRPA gasps]
What are these prints?

00:17:25.628 --> 00:17:29.215 position:50% align:center
It's like a meko,
but it's too big!

00:17:29.299 --> 00:17:30.842 position:50% align:center
[SHIRAISHI]
What's a meko?

00:17:30.925 --> 00:17:32.093 position:50% align:center
A big cat.

00:17:32.177 --> 00:17:35.221 position:50% align:center
It means
"those that die in cold."

00:17:35.305 --> 00:17:38.391 position:50% align:center
Couldn't you guys manage
to find him a cuter name?

00:17:38.475 --> 00:17:40.894 position:50% align:center
Definitely the prints
of a mountain cat.

00:17:40.977 --> 00:17:43.938 position:50% align:center
A meko oyasi?
Could it really be?

00:17:44.022 --> 00:17:46.858 position:50% align:center
So this is the cat monster
that Aca told me about!

00:17:46.941 --> 00:17:49.027 position:50% align:center
I've never seen one before!

00:17:50.653 --> 00:17:53.156 position:50% align:center
[WILK] Everything. Their shoes,
their clothes, their bags,

00:17:53.239 --> 00:17:55.158 position:50% align:center
their ropes, it was all gone.

00:17:55.241 --> 00:17:57.869 position:50% align:center
It was assumed that
the meko oyasi ate it up!

00:17:57.952 --> 00:17:59.788 position:50% align:center
Tobacco and all?

00:17:59.871 --> 00:18:01.790 position:50% align:center
[KIRORANKE] Mm-hmm.
Wilk and I actually hunted one

00:18:01.873 --> 00:18:03.958 position:50% align:center
together one time.

00:18:04.042 --> 00:18:06.336 position:50% align:center
And we sure did make
a ton off of that pelt.

00:18:06.419 --> 00:18:08.088 position:50% align:center
How'd it taste?!

00:18:08.171 --> 00:18:10.423 position:50% align:center
[KIRORANKE]
Not good. Very gamy.

00:18:10.507 --> 00:18:15.053 position:50% align:center
In fact, if I remember
correctly, your father hated it.

00:18:15.136 --> 00:18:17.764 position:50% align:center
I see. He hated it, huh?

00:18:17.847 --> 00:18:20.433 position:50% align:center
That's very good to know.

00:18:20.517 --> 00:18:23.687 position:50% align:center
I enjoy learning
new things about Aca!

00:18:25.605 --> 00:18:27.649 position:50% align:center
You want to know more about him?

00:18:28.900 --> 00:18:32.362 position:50% align:center
There's a woman who knew
the old Wilk well.

00:18:32.445 --> 00:18:35.115 position:50% align:center
Her name is Sofia.

00:18:35.198 --> 00:18:37.033 position:50% align:center
She was well-educated.

00:18:37.117 --> 00:18:38.368 position:50% align:center
And brave.

00:18:38.451 --> 00:18:40.870 position:50% align:center
She was a wonderful leader.

00:18:44.708 --> 00:18:47.293 position:50% align:center
She also happened
to be beautiful.

00:18:47.377 --> 00:18:51.673 position:50% align:center
Wilk and I both admired and
respected her a great deal.

00:18:51.756 --> 00:18:56.177 position:50% align:center
Aca did? I didn't
know she existed.

00:18:56.261 --> 00:18:58.388 position:50% align:center
I want to meet her.

00:18:58.471 --> 00:19:00.640 position:50% align:center
Do you know where she is now?

00:19:00.724 --> 00:19:04.853 position:50% align:center
Aleksandrovsk-Sakhalinsky.

00:19:04.936 --> 00:19:07.731 position:50% align:center
Or "Ako."

00:19:07.814 --> 00:19:10.108 position:50% align:center
[NARRATOR]
Aleksandrovsk-Sakhalinsky.

00:19:10.191 --> 00:19:12.068 position:50% align:center
Also known as "Ako."

00:19:12.152 --> 00:19:16.614 position:50% align:center
A major city in the Russian-
controlled section of Karafuto.

00:19:16.698 --> 00:19:21.244 position:50% align:center
Ever since 1858, the island of
Karafuto had been utilized as

00:19:21.327 --> 00:19:24.789 position:50% align:center
a place to exile criminals
from the mainland.

00:19:24.873 --> 00:19:30.128 position:50% align:center
And Ako was the spot where they
first landed when they arrived.

00:19:30.211 --> 00:19:34.382 position:50% align:center
Aleksandrovsk-Sakhalinsky
Prison, when filled to capacity,

00:19:34.466 --> 00:19:38.803 position:50% align:center
can hold about
1,700 prisoners, total.

00:19:38.887 --> 00:19:41.973 position:50% align:center
The male prisoners had half
their hair shaved off.

00:19:42.057 --> 00:19:44.142 position:50% align:center
They were primarily forced
to do hard labor

00:19:44.225 --> 00:19:46.353 position:50% align:center
in mining and construction.

00:19:46.436 --> 00:19:47.896 position:50% align:center
--[PRISON GUARD 31A grunting]
--[whip cracking]

00:19:47.979 --> 00:19:49.647 position:50% align:center
[NARRATOR] Those who tried to
escape would be brought back

00:19:49.731 --> 00:19:51.816 position:50% align:center
and whipped without question.

00:19:51.900 --> 00:19:54.736 position:50% align:center
Those who tried more than once
would be tied to a wheelbarrow

00:19:54.819 --> 00:19:57.614 position:50% align:center
that would stay with them
even as they ate and slept.

00:19:57.697 --> 00:20:00.075 position:50% align:center
[speaks Russian]

00:20:00.158 --> 00:20:04.621 position:50% align:center
[KIRORANKE] That's where Sofia
and her allies are being held.

00:20:04.704 --> 00:20:07.916 position:50% align:center
There was no evidence,
so they can't be executed.

00:20:07.999 --> 00:20:11.503 position:50% align:center
But they're kept hidden
away there in secret.

00:20:11.586 --> 00:20:16.132 position:50% align:center
She was the one behind our plot
to assassinate the emperor.

00:20:16.216 --> 00:20:21.554 position:50% align:center
[SOFIA speaks Russian]

00:20:24.349 --> 00:20:26.226 position:50% align:center
[KIRORANKE]
Sofia Goldenhand.

00:20:26.309 --> 00:20:28.645 position:50% align:center
She would commit crimes
in order to fund our activities

00:20:28.728 --> 00:20:31.314 position:50% align:center
with whatever she could steal.

00:20:31.398 --> 00:20:35.485 position:50% align:center
Because of that, she was given
the name "Golden Hand" at court.

00:20:36.986 --> 00:20:40.407 position:50% align:center
A woman?
A woman led your rebellion?

00:20:40.490 --> 00:20:42.492 position:50% align:center
[KIRORANKE]
Mm. She sure did.

00:20:42.575 --> 00:20:45.829 position:50% align:center
And she would know things
about Wilk that I don't know.

00:20:46.955 --> 00:20:51.001 position:50% align:center
[ASIRPA]
Hmm. Ako Prison...

00:20:51.084 --> 00:20:52.836 position:50% align:center
Here we come.

00:21:05.807 --> 00:21:08.226 position:50% align:center
[ASIRPA]
Ogata.

00:21:08.309 --> 00:21:10.145 position:50% align:center
Time to go.

00:21:15.483 --> 00:21:17.193 position:50% align:center
[ASIRPA]
You see something?

00:21:17.277 --> 00:21:18.820 position:50% align:center
Let's go.

00:23:09.723 --> 00:23:15.395 position:50% align:center
[SOFIA speaking Russian]

00:23:24.029 --> 00:23:26.031 position:50% align:center
--[thud]
--[SVETLANA gasps]

00:23:26.114 --> 00:23:29.659 position:50% align:center
[PRISON GUARD 31B
speaks Russian]

00:23:40.128 --> 00:23:42.172 position:50% align:center
[SOFIA sniffs]

00:23:45.258 --> 00:23:46.718 position:50% align:center
[SVETLANA]
Huh...?

00:23:49.262 --> 00:23:51.306 position:50% align:center
[SOFIA speaks Russian]

00:23:53.433 --> 00:23:56.269 position:50% align:center
[speaking Russian]

00:24:06.654 --> 00:24:09.616 position:50% align:center
[NARRATOR]
Next time: "Manslayer"!